'''Walter Bartky''' (1901–1958) was an American astronomer, applied mathematician, and educator, noteworthy for his role in the [[Manhattan Project]].<ref name=AHF>[http://www.atomicheritage.org/profile/walter-bartky Walter Bartky, Atomic Heritage Foundation]</ref>

==Education and career==
Walter Bartky received his B.S. from the University of Chicago in 1923 and his Ph.D. in 1926. At the University of Chicago he was an instructor in 1926, an assistant professor of astronomy from 1927 to 1932, and an associate professor of astronomy from 1932 to 1942. At the University of Chicago he became in 1943 a professor of applied mathematics and associate dean in the Division of Physical Sciences, served from 1945 to 1955 as the dean of the Division of Physical Sciences, and served from 1955 to 1958 as vice president in charge special scientific programs.<ref name=AHF/>

Walter Bartky was from 1926 to 1930 a consulting mathematician to Western Electric Company. In 1935 his book ''Highlights of Astronomy'' was published.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review of ''Highlights of Astronomy'' by Walter Bartky|journal=Popular Astronomy|volume=44|year=1936|pages=347–348|bibcode=1936PA.....44..347B}}</ref> During World War II he was the assistant director of the Manhattan Project's [[Metallurgical Laboratory]] at the University of Chicago.<ref name=AHF/>

In 1945 he was one of the signers of the [[Szilárd petition]]. In May 1945, he accompanied [[Leo Szilard]] and [[Harold Urey]] to [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] to present a memorandum to [[James F. Byrnes]]; the memorandum suggested that dropping an atomic bomb on Japan might start a nuclear arms race with the Soviet Union.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Smith, Ann Kimball|journal=Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|title= Behind the Decision to Use the Atomic Bomb: Chicago 1944–1945|date=October 1958|page= 296|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lgkAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA296}}</ref>

==Personal life==
On 9 January 1932, Walter Bartky married Elizabeth Inrig Robertson, of Glasgow, Scotland. The marriage produced two children, Walter Scott Bartky and Ian Robertson Bartky. W. Scott Bartky (1932–2010) was an engineer, entrepreneur and inventor with over 40 patents.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-01-05/news/1001040569_1_bead-computer-science-patents|title=Death Notice: Scott Bartky|date=5 January 2010|newspaper=Chicago Tribune}}</ref> Ian R. Bartky (1934–2007) was a physical chemist and historian of science.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Dick, Steven J.|title=Obituary: Ian R. Bartky, 1934–2007|journal=Bulletin of the Astronomical Society|date=January 2009|volume=41|page=565|bibcode=2009BAAS...41..565D}}</ref>

